_Mon, 20 October 2008 -- 10:00_

Na bitte, da habe ich es ja doch noch geschafft im Laufe der letzten Nacht das
Transcript des Pagan's Mind Interviews fertig zu kriegen. Es gibt leider ein
paar Passagen, welche ich aufgrund der lauten Hintergrundgeraeusche nicht sauber
rekonstruieren konnte; andererseits ist aber ziemlich klar, dass ich das
Gespraech nicht einfach so eins zu eins fuer den Artikel verwenden werde,
sondern wenigstens ein klein wenig aufraeume -- ich glaube die diversen "Hm" und
"Ahm" muss man nicht unbedingt in der gedruckten Version haben. Immerhin bin ich
aber schon einmal fuendig geworden was eine Ueberschrift betrifft, denn wenn
diese einmal gefunden ist liegt haeufig schon eine ungefaehre Idee vor, in
welche Richtung der Rest des Artikels gehen soll. Also bin ich jetzt dabei das
Gespraech ein wenig zu trimmen und in eine gut lesbare Form zu bringen.

Die wichtigen Nachrichten: Pagan's Mind arbeiten derzeit an einem Live Album,
welches -- wenn denn alles gut geht -- im Maerz/April kommenden Jahres
veroeffentlicht werden soll.

> Any plans for a new album?
>
> _I think the first thing we really want to do now, because we have been gathering a lot of live material... so I think if everything goes according to our plans and that we get to agree with our label, then we will release a live DVD maybe in March/April. So the main concert will be filmed on Oslo, the first of November. But we have some other stuff as well._
>
> So, there's still tickets for that?
>
> _I think it's sold out, but I don't know - it's the first gig with Sonata, but that night we are playing in our own country, so they give us also the full big stage and and we get a full set and everything - so it's very nice. So, we'll record that and... but now also we have started to work on the new album. So I guess that this process we start now, with serious working - but I think we may be ready for recording in one year. So maybe then March now, in 2009, we will release the live DVD and maybe early 2010 the new **Pagan's Mind** album, I think._

Interessant war auch zu erfahren, wo so die musikalischen Wurzeln der Band liegen:

> _I'm not the biggest fan of progressive music, but it's still... I mean lot of my influences are more from classic hard rock from the 70s and stuff -- like **Deep Purple**, **Led Zeppelin** and **Van Halen** and stuff, that's the biggest stuff for me. But it's a merge of people doing a lot of things. We never sat down and said that "Oh, we are going to be a progressive metal band", we never did that. It's like... the bass player, of course, he like likes lot of progressive music and the keyboard player is into a lot of fusion and stuff -- likes bands as **Toto** and stuff. And you have the drummer, he likes classic metal, also bands like **Dimmu Borgir** and things like **Dream Theater**. We get together and what happens happens. And I guess from when we did "Celestial Entrance" in 2002, from that on we kind of set a formula -- that was **Pagan's Mind**. So more straight forward rock 'n' roll and melodic stuff and also blended with a lot of progressive elements. But I think the main thing in **Pagan's Mind** is metal music with good melodies... but also progressive elements. It's pretty intense, it's in your face. We're not sitting on the sofa, relaxing, playing -- you know it's a lot of energy being delivered to the people who are here._

Der Gitarrist eines der drei Headliner eines Prog-Festivals kein sonderlich
grosser Fan von progressiver Musik? Eine interessante Erkenntnis am Rande...
